  "texts": [
    "The statistical models of crowdsourcing, introduced by Phil Dawid and David Skene in 1979 [69] and expanded upon in Cultural Consensus Theory [70] (CCT) by Romney and colleagues, offer insights into assessing subjective judgments.",
    "CCT, particularly, recognizes the lack of a singular consensus in diverse opinions, a concept valuable for understanding and improving LLMs in handling varied, complex information.",
    "This principle has led to further advancements, including the fine-tuning of deep neural networks to align their outputs more closely with consensus beliefs.",
    "[71] 8 ConclusionIn our study, we performed a comparative analysis of seven general-purpose LLMs-GPT-4 Turbo, GPT-4, GPT-3.5 Turbo, Claude 2.1, Claude 2, Gemini 1.0 Pro, and PaLM 2-focusing on their zero-shot performance in the GMAT's quantitative and verbal sections, which are crucial for global business school admissions.",
    "GPT-4 Turbo stood out as the top performer, with the latest versions of the other models also showing significant improvements over their predecessors."
  ],
